{"altmetric_id":26447482,"counts":{"readers":{"mendeley":4,"citeulike":0,"connotea":0},"total":{"posts_count":15},"twitter":{"unique_users_count":15,"unique_users":["kamalsuthan","ClaessenLAB","houndz_bu","BriegelAriane","orietta_mas","Ana_I_Rico","seamus_holden","Olu_GH","Allister_Crow","Cwhitch","vickybiotech144","cjblondel","aiubsharif1","Diego_official2","Kamo_Valenzuela"],"posts_count":15}},"selected_quotes":["One toxin, two targets: CbtA inhibits the bacterial actin MreB and the bacterial tubulin FtsZ. ht\u2026","One toxin, two targets: CbtA inhibits the bacterial actin MreB and the bacterial tubulin FtsZ."],"citation":{"abstract":"The toxin components of toxin-antitoxin modules, found in bacterial plasmids, phages, and chromosomes, typically target a single macromolecule to interfere with an essential cellular process. An apparent exception is the chromosomally encoded toxin component of the E. coli CbtA\/CbeA toxin-antitoxin module, which can inhibit both cell division and cell elongation. A small protein of only 124 amino acids, CbtA, was previously proposed to interact with both FtsZ, a tubulin homolog that is essential for cell division, and MreB, an actin homolog that is essential for cell elongation. However, whether or not the toxic effects of CbtA are due to direct interactions with these predicted targets is not known. Here, we genetically separate the effects of CbtA on cell elongation and cell division, showing that CbtA interacts directly and independently with FtsZ and MreB. Using complementary genetic approaches, we identify the functionally relevant target surfaces on FtsZ and MreB, revealing that in both cases, CbtA binds to surfaces involved in essential cytoskeletal filament architecture. We show further that each interaction contributes independently to CbtA-mediated toxicity and that disruption of both interactions is required to alleviate the observed toxicity. Although several other protein modulators are known to target FtsZ, the CbtA-interacting surface we identify represents a novel inhibitory target. Our findings establish CbtA as a dual function toxin that inhibits both cell division and cell elongation via direct and independent interactions with FtsZ and MreB.","altmetric_jid":"4f6fa5123cf058f61000334a","authors":["Danielle M. Heller","Mrinalini Tavag","Ann Hochschild"],"doi":"10.1371\/journal.pgen.1007007","first_seen_on":"2017-09-22T17:45:12+00:00","funders":["niehs"],"handles":[],"issns":["1553-7404"],"issue":"9","journal":"PLoS Genetics","last_mentioned_on":1506283861,"links":["http:\/\/journals.plos.org\/plosgenetics\/article?id=10.1371\/journal.pgen.1007007"],"pdf_url":"http:\/\/journals.plos.org\/plosgenetics\/article\/file?id=10.1371\/journal.pgen.1007007&type=printable","pmid":"28931012","pubdate":"2017-09-20T00:00:00+00:00","publisher":"Public Library of Science","publisher_subjects":[{"name":"Genetics","scheme":"era"}],"scopus_subjects":["Life Sciences","Medicine","Health Sciences","Agricultural and Biological Sciences","Biochemistry, Genetics and Molecular Biology"],"startpage":"e1007007","subjects":["genetics"],"title":"CbtA toxin of Escherichia coli inhibits cell division and cell elongation via direct and independent interactions with FtsZ and MreB","type":"article","volume":"13","mendeley_url":"http:\/\/www.mendeley.com\/research\/cbta-toxin-escherichia-coli-inhibits-cell-division-cell-elongation-via-direct-independent-interactio"},"altmetric_score":{"score":9.7,"score_history":{"1y":9.7,"6m":9.7,"3m":9.7,"1m":9.7,"1w":0,"6d":0,"5d":0,"4d":0,"3d":0,"2d":0,"1d":0,"at":9.7},"context_for_score":{"all":{"total_number_of_other_articles":8457084,"mean":7.1060307514935,"rank":925467,"this_scored_higher_than_pct":89,"this_scored_higher_than":7530425,"rank_type":"exact","sample_size":8457084,"percentile":89},"similar_age_3m":{"total_number_of_other_articles":119965,"mean":11.805278000067,"rank":18317,"this_scored_higher_than_pct":84,"this_scored_higher_than":101607,"rank_type":"exact"